{"title":["configfix interactive configuration conflict resolution for the linux kernel"],"author":[{"rawString":"patrick franz"},{"rawString":"thorsten berger"},{"rawString":"ibrahim fayaz"},{"rawString":"sarah nadi"},{"rawString":"evgeny groshev"}],"abstract":["Highly configurable systems are highly complex systems, with the Linux kernel arguably being one of most well-known ones. Since 2007, it has been a frequent target research community, conducting empirical studies and building dedicated methods tools for analyzing, configuring, testing, optimizing, maintaining in light its vast configuration space. However, despite large body work, mainly bug fixes that were result such made back into kernel's source tree. Unfortunately, users still struggle resolving conflicts, since largely lacks automated support. Additionally, there technical community requirements supporting conflict resolution kernel, as, example, using pure C-based solution uses only compatible third-party libraries (if any). With aim contributing to we present CONFIGFIX, tooling integrated configurator, is purely implemented C, finally working able produce conflicts. In this experience report, describe our experiences ranging over decade upon work from on mechanisms as well how designed realized CONFIGFIX while adhering standards. While helps obtaining their desired configuration, sound semantic abstraction implement provides basis many above techniques helping researchers developers."],"numberOfReferences":[55],"numberOfCitations":[],"year":2020,"publisher":[],"type":"Repository","pdf":["http://arxiv.org/pdf/2012.15342.pdf","http://export.arxiv.org/pdf/2012.15342","https://arxiv.org/abs/2012.15342","https://export.arxiv.org/abs/2012.15342"],"uniqueId":[{"type":"DOI"},{"type":"MicrosoftAcademic","value":3117583373}],"source":["microsoftAcademic"]}
