{"title":["Projecting A Modular Future"],"author":[{"rawString":"markus voelter"},{"rawString":"jos warmer"},{"rawString":"bernd kolb"}],"abstract":["Two innovations are enhancing programming languages' capabilities. First, modularity lets you combine independently developed languages without changing their respective definitions. A language is no longer a fixed quantity; can extend it with domain-specific constructs as needed. Second, projectional editing build editors and IDEs that don't require parsers. Such support range of tightly integrated notations, including textual, symbolic, tabular, graphical notations. In addition, by avoiding parsers, they avoid grammar composition's well-known limitations. Three examples illustrate how these two affect programming-language design. set modular extensions C for embedded enables efficient code generation formal analysis. requirements engineering flexibly combines structured unstructured (prose) data. Finally, defining insurance rules uses mathematical notation. These all rely on the open source JetBrains MPS (Meta Programming System) workbench. This article part special issue Software Architecture."],"numberOfReferences":[11,5],"numberOfCitations":[17,9],"year":2015,"publisher":["IEEE"],"type":"Journal article","pdf":["https://doi.org/10.1109/MS.2014.103","http://www.voelter.de/data/pub/projectingModuleFuture.pdf","https://dblp.uni-trier.de/db/journals/software/software32.html#VoelterWK15","https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/6866847/","http://www.voelter.de/data/pub/projectingModuleFuture.pdf"],"uniqueId":[{"type":"DOI","value":"10.1109/MS.2014.103"},{"type":"MicrosoftAcademic","value":2045945686},{"type":"DOI","value":"10.1109/ms.2014.103"}],"source":["microsoftAcademic","openCitations"],"sourceTitle":"Ieee Software"}
