{"title":["parsing expression grammars a recognition based syntactic foundation"],"author":[{"rawString":"bryan ford"}],"abstract":["For decades we have been using Chomsky's generative system of grammars, particularly context-free grammars (CFGs) and regular expressions (REs), to express the syntax programming languages protocols. The power ambiguity is crucial their original purpose modelling natural languages, but this very makes it unnecessarily difficult both parse machine-oriented CFGs. Parsing Expression Grammars (PEGs) provide an alternative, recognition-based formal foundation for describing syntax, which solves problem by not introducing in first place. Where CFGs nondeterministic choice between alternatives, PEGs instead use prioritized choice. address frequently felt expressiveness limitations REs, simplifying definitions making unnecessary separate lexical hierarchical components. A linear-time parser can be built any PEG, avoiding complexity fickleness LR parsers inefficiency generalized CFG parsing. While a rich set operators constructing they are reducible two minimal recognition schemas developed around 1970, TS/TDPL gTS/GTDPL, here proven equivalent effective power."],"numberOfReferences":[27],"numberOfCitations":[354],"year":2004,"publisher":["ACM"],"type":"Conference paper","pdf":["https://ece.uwaterloo.ca/%7Evganesh/TEACHING/W2014/lectures/lecture16.pdf","http://portal.acm.org/citation.cfm?doid=964001.964011","https://dblp.uni-trier.de/db/conf/popl/popl2004.html#Ford04","https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/964001.964011","https://doi.org/10.1145/964001.964011","https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=964001.964011","https://doi.acm.org/10.1145/964001.964011"],"uniqueId":[{"type":"DOI","value":"10.1145/964001.964011"},{"type":"MicrosoftAcademic","value":2018045485}],"source":["microsoftAcademic"]}
