{"title":["model driven architecture foundations and applications"],"author":[{"rawString":"arend rensink"}],"abstract":["The OMG's Model Driven Architecture (MDA) initiative has been the focus of much attention in both academia and industry, due to its promise more rapid consistent software development through increased use models. In order for MDA reach full potential, ability manipulate transform models -most obviously from Platform Independent (PIM) Specic Models (PSM)- is vital. Recognizing this need, OMG issued a Request For Proposals (RFP) largely concerned with nding suitable mechanism transforming This paper outlines relevant background material, summarizes approach taken by QVT-Partners (to whom authors belong), presents non-trivial example using approach, nally sketches out what future holds model transformations."],"numberOfReferences":[],"numberOfCitations":[368],"year":2008,"publisher":[],"type":"Book","pdf":["https://core.ac.uk/display/91984996","http://www.gbv.de/dms/ilmenau/toc/529142430.PDF","http://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2009LNCS.5562.....P/abstract","https://link.springer.com/10.1007/978-3-540-72901-3","https://openlibrary.org/books/OL28305325M/Model-Driven_Architecture_-_Foundations_and_Applications","https://research.utwente.nl/en/publications/model-driven-architecture-foundations-and-applications-3","https://utwente-staging.elsevierpure.com/en/publications/model-driven-architecture-foundations-and-applications-3","https://www.amazon.com/Model-Driven-Architecture-Warmer-Arend-Rensink/dp/3540826297","http://doc.utwente.nl/41391/1/000000ca.pdf"],"uniqueId":[{"type":"DOI"},{"type":"MicrosoftAcademic","value":2146486372}],"source":["microsoftAcademic"]}
{"title":["antlr a predicated ll k parser generator"],"author":[{"rawString":"terence parr"},{"rawString":"russell w quong"}],"abstract":["SUMMARY Despite the parsing power of LR=LALR algorithms, e.g. YACC, programmers often choose to write recursive-descent parsers by hand obtain increased flexibility, better error handling, and ease debugging. We introduce ANTLR, a public-domain parser generator that combines flexibility hand-coded with convenience generator, which is component PCCTS. ANTLR has many features make it easier use than other language tools. Most important, provides predicates let programmer systematically direct parse via arbitrary expressions using semantic syntactic context; in practice, eliminates need hand-tweak output, even for difficult problems. also integrates description lexical analysis, accepts LL(k) grammars k> 1with extended BNF notation, can automatically generate"],"numberOfReferences":[7],"numberOfCitations":[489],"year":1995,"publisher":["John Wiley & Sons, Inc."],"type":"Journal article","pdf":["https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=213603","https://dx.doi.org/10.1002/spe.4380250705","http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.15.70&rep=rep1&type=pdf","https://core.ac.uk/display/24350650","https://dblp.uni-trier.de/db/journals/spe/spe25.html#ParrQ95","https://doi.org/10.1002/spe.4380250705","https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/spe.4380250705","http://doi.org/10.1002/spe.4380250705"],"uniqueId":[{"type":"DOI","value":"10.1002/SPE.4380250705"},{"type":"MicrosoftAcademic","value":2018951244}],"source":["microsoftAcademic"]}
{"title":["sugarj library based syntactic language extensibility"],"author":[{"rawString":"sebastian erdweg"},{"rawString":"tillmann rendel"},{"rawString":"christian kastner"},{"rawString":"klaus ostermann"}],"abstract":["Existing approaches to extend a programming language with syntactic sugar often leave bitter taste, because they cannot be used the same ease as main extension mechanism of - libraries. Sugar libraries are novel approach for syntactically extending within language. A library is like an ordinary library, but can, in addition, export using library. maintain composability and scoping properties hence particularly well-suited embedding multitude domain-specific languages into host They also inherit self-applicability from libraries, which means that can provide extensions definition other To demonstrate expressiveness applicability we have developed SugarJ, on top Java, SDF Stratego, supports extensibility. SugarJ employs incremental parsing technique, allows changing syntax source file. We by five extensions, including embeddings XML closures all available illustrate utility Schema, metalanguage define languages."],"numberOfReferences":[47],"numberOfCitations":[121],"year":2011,"publisher":["ACM"],"type":"Conference paper","pdf":["https://doi.acm.org/10.1145/2076021.2048099","http://www.student.informatik.tu-darmstadt.de/~xx00seba/publications/sugarj.pdf","https://www.informatik.uni-marburg.de/~rendel/erdweg11sugarj.pdf","https://dblp.uni-trier.de/db/conf/oopsla/oopsla2011.html#ErdwegRKO11","https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/2048066.2048099","https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?doid=2048066.2048099"],"uniqueId":[{"type":"DOI","value":"10.1145/2048066.2048099"},{"type":"MicrosoftAcademic","value":2078200248}],"source":["microsoftAcademic"]}
{"title":["eco a language composition editor"],"author":[{"rawString":"lukas diekmann"},{"rawString":"laurence tratt"}],"abstract":["Language composition editors have traditionally fallen into two extremes: traditional parsing, which is inflexible or ambiguous; syntax directed editing, programmers dislike. In this paper we extend an incremental parser to create approach bridges the our prototype editor ‘feels’ like a normal text editor, but user always operates on valid tree as in editor. This allows us compose arbitrary syntaxes while still enabling IDE-like features such name binding analysis."],"numberOfReferences":[26],"numberOfCitations":[127],"year":2014,"publisher":["Springer, Cham"],"type":"Conference paper","pdf":["https://soft-dev.org/pubs/pdf/diekmann_tratt__eco_a_language_composition_editor.pdf","http://core.ac.uk/display/29948545","http://soft-dev.org/pubs/pdf/diekmann_tratt__eco_a_language_composition_editor.pdf","https://dblp.uni-trier.de/db/conf/sle/sle2014.html#DiekmannT14","https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_5","https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_5","https://rd.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_5"],"uniqueId":[{"type":"DOI","value":"10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_5"},{"type":"MicrosoftAcademic","value":1019674797}],"source":["microsoftAcademic"]}
